    "instruction": "Analyze logs to locate concrete failure timestamps and candidate root components (bounded outputs):\n1) From error_logs.csv: compute counts per timestamp (number of error log lines). Return the top 20 timestamps by count (columns: timestamp, count) and also report the earliest timestamp in the incident window (>= 1647736200 and <= 1647738000) that has any error_logs. Also return, for cmdb_id in (frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2), the distinct messages and for each message the earliest timestamp and total count (limit to top 20 messages overall).\n2) From log.csv: filter rows where log_name is 'log.error_count' or 'log.row_count'. For each timestamp within the incident window (>=1647736200 and <=1647738000) compute sum_error_count = sum(value for log.error_count across cmdb_ids) and sum_row_count = sum(value for log.row_count across cmdb_ids). Return the top 20 timestamps within the window sorted by sum_error_count descending, showing columns: timestamp, sum_error_count, sum_row_count. Also return, for frontend-0/1/2 only, the per-timestamp log.error_count values in-window but limit rows to top 20 timestamps with highest sum_error_count.\nKeep outputs compact and bounded. Do NOT return raw full logs; only the requested aggregates and top lists. Use the kernel's timestamp integers (do not convert to datetimes)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed global-threshold anomaly scans across metrics and traces, and aggregated anomalies to component level. Findings so far: (1) metric anomalies are widespread with earliest anomaly timestamps at the window start (1647736200) for many components; (2) trace anomaly results are not reliable because many trace series are zero-dominated (P95/P5 = 0) and our current rule flagged zeros as anomalies; (3) logs show concentrated frontend warnings: error_logs earliest in-window at 1647736202 with heavy counts for frontend-0 (229), frontend-2 (227), frontend-1 (80); normalized log.error_count also peaks at multiple timestamps (e.g., 1647736380, 1647736920, 1647737280), with frontends contributing most of the per-timestamp error_count. This suggests frontend pods are strongly implicated and we must now inspect frontend metric KPIs (resource metrics and JVM metrics) to determine the exact failure times and reasons for the two failures within 08:30–09:00. Traces are currently not discriminating, so we will rely on frontend metrics and logs to localize root causes and occurrence times.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Focus on frontend pods (frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2). Using the metric anomaly scan results available in kernel (result_table and the component-level aggregates), produce a compact per-series table for only these three cmdb_id values with the following columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_P95, global_P5, anomaly_count_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, anomaly_max_value, anomaly_min_value, total_points_in_window, and max_relative_deviation (use the same series_deviation formula previously used). Return rows sorted first by earliest_anomaly_timestamp ascending, then by max_relative_deviation descending. Limit output to top 50 rows (or fewer if not that many series exist). Also, separately return for each frontend pod the earliest error_logs timestamp and its error_logs count (from error_logs.csv) and the per-pod sum of log.error_count at that earliest timestamp (from log.csv). Keep outputs compact and bounded; do not return raw full time series."}

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the prescribed workflow: computed global thresholds for metrics and traces, scanned the 08:30–09:00 window, aggregated anomalies to component level, and examined traces and logs. Results point to frontend pods (frontend-0/1/2) as the primary locus of observed failures: error_logs are dominated by a repeating warning \"failed to retrieve...\" with earliest in-window occurrence at 1647736202, and normalized log.error_count shows multiple high peaks (e.g., timestamps 1647736380, 1647736920, 1647737280) where frontends contribute the majority of errors. Metric anomalies are widespread starting at the window start (1647736200), but many trace-series anomalies are artifacts because global P95/P5 are zero. To localize two distinct failure events we need to pick concrete candidate timestamps (the likely failure occurrence minutes) and then inspect frontend resource and JVM KPIs at those minutes to determine the underlying reason for each failure. The next atomic step is to identify the top error peaks (timestamps) in-window with per-frontend breakdown and corresponding error_log counts so we can select the two failure minutes to inspect in detail.",
